^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Let's talk about my preempt. I have close to an opening hand but, in third seat, I felt it was a good tactic. My partner is a passed hand, so it is unlikely we have game and I am short in the majors, so it is likely they can outbid us in a major. It turns out they do have a heart fit. They will lose two hearts and a spade probably, perhaps one more. So, they are likely making at least three hearts. If I pass, and Eddy opens 1N, they probably get to 3H. So, I basically broke even and might beat a few pairs who venture to 4.|
PG| ***** 17 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|As to the play, at trick one I pitched my King of hearts not so much as a false card, as a way to get an entry to dummy. I was hoping East had the Ace of diamonds and therefore might only lose two diamond tricks. If I dont do that, I have no entry to dummy. Now as to the defense. The lead was fine. All other leads are likely to lose a trick. And because I pitched the @HK, Kerrie's spade shift was fine as well. I don't blame Eddy for leading a club, although he should probably play the Ace first and see how Kerrie signals. It did, however, out the club play cost him a trick. On the other hand, however, neither hearts nor spades looks right. I agree with playing a club, but I think the Ace is slightly better although playing any club is costly as it turns out.|
